---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { articleSchema, faqSchema } from '../../../data/schema.js';
import { topics } from '../../../data/ages.js';

const title = '3–6 Month Old Development: What to Expect';
const description = 'Between 3 and 6 months, babies undergo a major transformation. They move from newborn reflexes to voluntary actions, start showing distinct personalities, and prepare for the major milestone of starting solids.';

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'When should I start solid foods?',
    answer: 'The AAP and CDC recommend waiting until about 6 months of age to introduce solid foods. Signs of readiness include being able to sit with little or no support, having good head control, showing interest in what you are eating, and the disappearance of the tongue-thrust reflex.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How much sleep does a 3–6 month old need?',
    answer: 'At this age, most babies need 12–16 hours of sleep in a 24-hour period, including naps. Many babies begin to develop more predictable sleep patterns and may start sleeping longer stretches at night, though the "4-month sleep regression" is common as their sleep cycles mature.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Is it normal for my baby to drool so much at 4 months?',
    answer: 'Yes, excessive drooling is very common at this age. While it can be a sign of teething, it is often just a result of the salivary glands maturing and the baby exploring their mouth with their hands and toys.',
  },
  {
    question: 'When will my baby start rolling over?',
    answer: 'Most babies begin to roll from stomach to back around 4 months, and from back to stomach around 5 or 6 months. Tummy time is essential for building the muscle strength needed for this milestone.',
  },
];

const aSchema = articleSchema({
  title,
  description,
  url: 'https://ageexpectations.com/ages/3-6-months/',
});
const fSchema = faqSchema(faqs);
---
<BaseLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  articleSchema={aSchema}
  faqSchema={fSchema}
  breadcrumbs={[
    { label: '3–6 Months' },
  ]}
>
  <h1>3–6 Month Old Development: What to Expect</h1>

  <p>The period between 3 and 6 months is often a favorite for parents. Your baby is likely "waking up" to the world, offering frequent social smiles, laughing, and beginning to interact with their environment in more intentional ways. This is a season of rapid physical and cognitive growth as your baby moves away from involuntary newborn reflexes and begins to master voluntary movements.</p>

  <p>This guide covers the key developmental areas for babies aged 3 to 6 months, following guidelines from the American Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) and the CDC.</p>

  <h2>Explore 3–6 Month Topics</h2>
  <div class="topic-grid">
    {topics.map(topic => (
      <a href={`/ages/3-6-months/${topic.slug}/`} class="topic-card">{topic.label}</a>
    ))}
  </div>

  <h2>Physical Milestones: Moving and Grooving</h2>

  <p>By 4 to 6 months, your baby's neck and trunk muscles are getting much stronger. Key milestones include:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Rolling:</strong> Many babies learn to roll from tummy to back by 4 months, and both ways by 6 months.</li>
    <li><strong>Sitting:</strong> By 6 months, many babies can sit with support, and some can sit briefly without help using their arms for balance (the "tripod" position).</li>
    <li><strong>Reaching and Grasping:</strong> Your baby is now using their hands intentionally to reach for, grab, and pull objects toward them. Everything they grab will likely end up in their mouth — this is how they explore!</li>
    <li><strong>Tummy Time:</strong> This remains crucial. A 4-month-old should be able to push up onto their elbows or even straight arms during tummy time.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Communication and Social Skills</h2>

  <p>Your baby is becoming a social butterfly! Expect more intentional interaction:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Social Smiling and Laughing:</strong> By 4 months, most babies smile spontaneously at people and have started to chuckle or laugh out loud.</li>
    <li><strong>Babbling:</strong> "Cooing" turns into "babbling." You'll hear more consonant sounds like "m," "b," and "p" (e.g., "muh-muh" or "bah-bah").</li>
    <li><strong>Responding to Names:</strong> By 6 months, many babies begin to recognize and respond to their own names.</li>
    <li><strong>Expressing Emotions:</strong> You'll notice distinct cries for hunger, pain, or tiredness, and clear expressions of joy or frustration.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Sleep Patterns and Regressions</h2>

  <p>Sleep at 3–6 months often becomes more consolidated at night, but it can also be disrupted by the "4-month sleep regression." This is actually a sign of brain development, as your baby's sleep architecture changes to be more like an adult's. Most babies at this age need two to three naps a day. The AAP continues to recommend room-sharing and placing babies on their backs on a firm, flat surface for every sleep.</p>

  <h2>Feeding: Preparing for Solids</h2>

  <p>Until 6 months, the AAP recommends exclusive breastfeeding or formula feeding. However, between 4 and 6 months, your baby may start showing signs of readiness for solid foods. Milk remains the primary source of nutrition, but you can look for these signs:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Good head and neck control.</li>
    <li>Ability to sit up with little or no support.</li>
    <li>Loss of the "extrusion reflex" (pushing food out of the mouth with the tongue).</li>
    <li>Significant interest in what you are eating.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="faq-section">
    <h2>Is This Normal? Common Questions About 3–6 Month Development</h2>
    {faqs.map(faq => (
      <div class="faq-item">
        <p class="faq-question">{faq.question}</p>
        <p class="faq-answer">{faq.answer}</p>
      </div>
    ))}
  </div>

  <div class="callout">
    <h2>When to Talk to Your Pediatrician</h2>
    <p>The AAP recommends well-child visits at 4 months and 6 months. Contact your pediatrician if your baby:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Doesn't watch things as they move.</li>
      <li>Doesn't smile at people.</li>
      <li>Can't hold their head steady.</li>
      <li>Doesn't coo or make sounds.</li>
      <li>Doesn't bring things to their mouth.</li>
      <li>Doesn't push down with their legs when feet are placed on a hard surface.</li>
      <li>Has trouble moving one or both eyes in all directions.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Always trust your instincts as a parent. If you have concerns about your baby's development, your pediatrician is your best resource.</p>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
